This count includes spaces.
So `asciiSpaceCount / textChars` gives the ratio of spaces to printable chars.
If > 5%, return true. This seems like a reasonable heuristic for text files (sentences have spaces).

If a file has no textChars (e.g., all nulls, caught earlier) or all high bytes (no spaces, like Japanese text), this check fails. It falls through to `return (textChars / buffer.length) > 0.9;`.
For Japanese text (all high bytes), `textChars` is high, `buffer.length` is same, ratio is 1.0 > 0.9, returns true. Good.

